segments.text: Another of the things that I thought would do well to discuss, and that you've been quite analytical of the situation all through the years, it just does help a whole lot to be bound together in association where we can learn not only the technological things, but learn how to get along together and with each other and to promote veterinary medicine for the benefit of the public.
As an active person all through these years,
I'm sure you espoused those views.
Yes, that was one thing that we as board members were made to realize that that was our primary purpose was to benefit the public.
And I appeared before the Sunset Commission
at the last two or three years, three years ago, four years ago, I guess, when the veterinary board came under review.
And that was the time that they proposed to put lay people on the veterinary board, examining board.
And it was, to me, I think it was a mistake, but
The legislature didn't seem to think so, and we did wind up with two members.
But, you know, you have to have gone through a veterinary school to appreciate what we can do and the services that we do render.
And what needs to be done.
Yeah.
It's just, I think the name of the game, as far as I'm concerned, is your client-veterinary relationship.
That's just my feeling of it, and you can't get away from it.
And I've seen so many newer graduates that, and I'm not setting myself up as an example, but so many newer graduates that the only thing they're looking for is the dollar.
And it's, there's more to it than that.

For, I can't help but notice some of their veterinarians as they've gone through the practice career, the ones who've just made an adequate living seem to be just as happy as many of those who have made a
greater amount of money, so.
Yeah.
Well, very few, very few veterinarians ever got rich practicing veterinary medicine.
A small percentage of them.
The ones that got that made it on the...
They made it on investments or some outside interest.
On the side, yes.
One of the things that I thought, since you've been around quite a while, is to
discuss some of the acquaintances that you've known in veterinary medicine through the years.
One of those grand people that we don't hear about and used to be secretary of the TVMA back in the early days was Dr. Marsteller.
What are your recollections of Dr. Marsteller?
Well, of course, he was dean when I went to school, say, at A&M.
He was the dean.
And I thought Dr. Marsteller was a very fine man.
He was always receptive to any problems that I had.
And I felt free to go in any time and just ask him anything that I wanted, and his door was always open.
And he was a fine man.
He was a very dedicated person.
He was secretary back in the times when your dad was very active in the association.
Did you ever hear your dad talk about him in the association?
Oh, yeah.
My dad and Dr. Marsteller were real close friends.
And I first got to know him when my dad would go down for short courses at A&M during the summer.
And I would go with him and got to know Dr. Marsteller.
I'd stay over at the horse barn with Owen Garrigan.
I don't know whether you ever knew Owen Garrigan or not.
He was the greatest horseman that ever left A&M.
And he had charge of all the horse barn, all the horses, and I'd stay over there with him a lot.
And later on, when I went to school, I got me a job over there working for him.
I didn't care about, of course, I needed the money, but he forgot more about horses than most people down there ever knew.
He was a wonderful Scotchman, and he was a wonderful horseman.
Wonderful.
There's another man I thought I'd ask you about.
During the World War I years, Dr. N.F.
Williams was
president for three years.
You know, he spanned the war years.
Did either you or your father have a personal acquaintance with him?
No, I never had any acquaintance.
I was never acquainted with Dr. Williams.
Was he in vet school?
He was in the ag department, wasn't he?
No, he was a veterinarian in practice.
I forget just where he practiced.
But when the
Two associations came together again after they'd been separated for four years.
He seemed to be oil on troubled waters, and that's why I thought it had something to do with it.
No, I've never heard his name mentioned.
If I have, I've forgotten it.
Okay.
Another person who really worked hard stayed mostly in the laboratory, but he did get out around.
I know I saw him in a lot of the veterinary meetings and so forth.
Just to see him was Dr. Hubert Schmidt.
Did you see much of him?
I worked with Dr. Schmidt when I was in school, and he was working on X disease.
Are you familiar with that?
It's a toxic disease, is that correct?
Yes.
He did a lot of research on that.
You might tell us the etiology of that while you're on it.
Somebody might hear this and didn't know what it was even.
Well, it was a
Actually, it was caused from lubricant that was used in making these range pellets.
And the first that I saw it, the first case I had, I didn't know what it was.
It was just the cows, the cattle, their muzzle,
Those would just crust up and be red just like it was a photosensitization.
They're utter, all the light spots.
And it was caused from chlorinated naphthalenes in the lubricant that was also lubricants that was used on farm machinery.
I think Texaco was involved in it.
I know Trader's Mill in Fort Worth was involved in it.
And incidentally, they are to be complimented because they paid every claim I guess that was presented to them without any... Was Dr. Schmidt the one that finally came up with the solution?
I think so.
I think you did.
I know he did more research on X disease than anyone else that I know of.
I know I had one client that came to me and had lost 86 head of cattle.
And the only way that I diagnosed it or knew what it was while I was

I took one of the tags from a feed sack in his barn and I don't know I stuck it in my pocket and he had told me that his wife had never lost any hadn't lost any cattle with this and I said well how do you account for that he said I don't know but he said she won't buy she won't buy feed from the same people I buy from so I guess that

little spark or something i got back to my office and i called dr star i believe in gainful and i see star i believe i believe it's dr star and i said doctor i said who are these people that you're having losses from who are they buying their feed from and he's kind of hesitant to tell him
And finally he told me who it was.
I said, well, it's the same place mine's coming from.
And that, I think, was to, as far as I was concerned, was the source of the problem.
Who were the other people of prominence that you felt came along that deserve mention through the years?
Well, Dr. Phil Mockford practiced here in Greenville.
He was the first class that graduated from A&M.
He just died a couple of years ago.
And he was quite prominent with the State Association.
Was that in 1920?
What?
The first class that graduated from A&M?
I don't remember the date.
I know he was in the first class.
There were only...
There were very few graduates from it.
Someone told me that no one in that class ever went into practice, but that can't be true.
He did.
No, that's not true.
Dr. Mockford, right?
M-O-G-F-O-R-D?
M-O-C-K-F-O-R-D. Oh, M-O-C-K-F-O-R-D. J. Phil.
J. Phil Mockford.
And I've seen pictures of that class somewhere.
I don't remember.
There were eight of them, weren't there?
Something like that, yeah.
I feel that Dr. Al Price needs a big pat on the back for getting the physical plant enlarged at A&M and so forth.
They were kind of cramped over there where they originally were.
Yeah, Al stepped in at a good time and did a real fine job.
He's to be commended for it.
He deserves a lot of credit.
He was a classmate of mine.
I couldn't help but feel that in the examining board, compared to the mild situations that used to be, there weren't too many cases to follow up on, and the examinations were relatively...

homegrown now you've got to coordinate with the national board and all that sort of thing the examination board work has become much more complex in the last 15 years has it not yeah and i was i was in the middle of that too tell us about that well the professional examination service is the is the mother of the national exam and they

wanted to well the first meeting that I went to after I was we had what's called the American Association of State Boards which are members from state boards from each state and the National Examination Service wasn't giving us the service that we felt we should have they had repeat questions and they had a bank of questions that were
antiquated questions that you wouldn't believe were still there and this was back in 1970.
So T.D.
Weaver deserves more credit for than anyone else for the work that was done to to improve the national examination and the state our whole state board exam.
T.D.
's never gotten the
credit that he deserved.
But I was president of the board, and we were in Anaheim, California, and T.B.
and I got the board president from Colorado, Whitey Albrecht from California.
I've forgotten his name.
One from Washington State.
one from Kansas, one from Oklahoma, Sam Strong from Oklahoma.
And we told the National Board, National Examining Service, if they didn't improve it and do what we wanted, we were going to pull out of it.
Well, they couldn't operate without us.
So they did improve it, and the national exam improved, I think, tremendously the next
from then on.
I haven't seen one lately, but I know it was a big thing.
I know I served on the National Examining Board, and we would go up every year and go through those questions and see that there were new questions, fresh questions, and it made a big difference.
They were just giving us anything they wanted, and it was no good.
Also, it's much more complex as regards the possibilities of malpractice and so forth now, is it not?
With the attorneys becoming much more active in the field of this and that, they're ambitious both from the standpoint of
protecting someone who perhaps ought to be reprimanded and also for bringing frivolous suits about.
Well, I'm sure that veterinary profession gets its share of them.
I don't know it's I don't think we see near as many malpractice suits as possibly they should be.
It's
You don't realize just how much is involved until you start reading all the complaints that come into the examining board that have to be answered.
And the people that complain, they feel like they have a legitimate complaint, which they do.
I'm sure they feel like they do, and most of them are.
There's room for it, but the big problem
that could help avoid so many of these is communication.
You know that being in practice that you have good days and you have bad days and it's pretty easy to brush them off if you're not careful and that's the big problem.
I don't think it's that they don't know what they're doing but I think that it's
They just don't communicate with the client.
If the client understands everything before they leave, it eliminates a lot of problems, doesn't it?
It's always done.
Sure enough.
Anything else you wish to give for the good of the cause while you're telling how everything is?
I think it would be well...
You're one of the fine people who has become involved a whole lot civically, and I think it's well to tell all your civic positions here in the city of Greenville.
Well, I've served on the school board for 12 years.
I was president of it for six years.
I served on the city council for two terms, and I was mayor for one term.
And that was...
Six years on city council, 12 years on school board.
Served 12 years on state examining board.
Served three years on the national board of examiners.
President of the American Association of State Boards.
And I was representative of the state boards to FARB, which is a federation of
Association of Health.
I don't know.
I've forgotten.
It's been 10 years.
Federal Association of Related Boards?
Not related board.
Federal Association of Health.
F-A-H-R-B, of Health.
Uh.
I don't know, it doesn't matter a whole lot, but it was an interesting job for a while.
But I've been active in Chamber of Commerce and in Greenville and tried to be a good citizen.
Very fine.
Dr. Wilkins, we certainly appreciate all the contributions that you and your father before you have made for the veterinary profession, and we're looking forward to many more years of such service.
Well, thank you, Bob.
